Humeral process of cleithrum small, short and rather blunt. Axillary pore (see Friel & Vigliotta 2006 ; Wright & Page 2006 :
Fig. 2
) present, small and situated just below lower border of humeral process. Its presence seems to be the first record for the genus as well as the family.

In live specimens, the overall body colour of some individuals is far more light brown. In addition, based on a single photograph (
Fig. 2
) of a freshly collected specimen, some specimens present 7 or 8 transverse series of black spots in life. However, most of the small as well as large sized specimens lack these spots, both when freshly collected or preserved. There are only two preserved specimens [MRAC A 5-36 -P- 119 (111.0 mm SL) and MRAC A 7-13 -P- 29-41 ( 175.6 mm SL)] where these spots are still visible.
